Converting each column within the data frame to be the right data type.

survey2 <- survey1 %>%
  mutate(
    Q2 = as.numeric(Q2),
    Q3 = as.logical(Q3),
    Q5 = as.numeric(Q5),
    Q10 = as.numeric(Q10),
    Q13 = as.numeric(Q13),
    Q20 = as.logical(Q20),
    Q21 = as.numeric(Q21),
    Q22 = as.integer(Q22),
    Q23 = as.integer(Q23),
    Q24 = as.numeric(Q24),
    Q33 = as.logical(Q33),
         )
ggplot(survey2,aes(x=Q18,fill=Q26))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill") + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Dark2")+
  labs(fill="Gender")+
  xlab("Activities") + ylab("Number of students")

As we can see in the graph, males and females do totally different activities during their break time. Additionally, in this survey, only girls choose to go to gym and hang out with friends which is a contrary result compared with common recognition.

ggplot(survey2,aes(x=Q8,fill=Q30))+
  geom_bar()+
  facet_grid(~Q26)+
  labs(fill="Struggled")+
  xlab ("Study hours per week")+ ylab("Number of students")

According to the graph, students who spend more than 12 hours a week in studying are less likely to struggle in this unit. This means porblem in this unit can be solved by hard working. Additionally, the proportion of confused students are approximately the same between males and females. So it is not reliable to say that males are good at computing.
